description: is available in our Fairfield, CA showroom and any inquiries may be directed to us at

New to our Fairfield showroom is this beautifully restored 1965 Ford Mustang 2 Door Coupe with red exterior paint and a black interior. It is a Factory "A" code muscle car it has a 289 CI V-8 engine under the hood with a 4-speed manual transmission, 380 gears, a Posi rear end and traction bars. It also has high performance cam roller rocker lifters, port matched heads and intake manifolds, an Edelbrock aluminum intake manifold, a Holley 650 double pumper carb, a Flowmaster dual exhaust and too many other upgrades to list.

This 1965 Ford Mustang was restored back in 1995 to very high standards and it has only been driven approximately 1500 miles since that time. While it does show some slight signs of aging, this one is incredibly impressive up close and it is an outstanding everyday driver. With great power/torque, a sweet growl from the engine and very nice traction, it is simply a pleasure to drive around the Bay Area in.

Additionally, this ’65 Mustang Coupe is a lifetime California classic that has both the black and yellow plates included in the sale. It also has Centerline aluminum wheels with brand new tires, the original factory AM/FM radio and a completely clean original dash with no cutouts for optional upgrades. This is simply a very well preserved classic that delivers exceptional performance.

Overall, this 1965 Ford Mustang is in phenomenal shape and it drives like it just pulled out of the factory showroom. With all the performance upgrades and such a clean look, this one is an absolute steal at the current asking price. It’s simply too nice to last for long at this price. description: We know you stopped to look at this 1965 Ford Mustang because it's a cool classic in a great color combo, and it's all for an affordable price.  But when you see that this coupe has also gone under a rotisserie restoration that even added A/C to the interior, well then, you know this is the perfect pony for you.

There are plenty of nice red Mustangs out there, so we tend to notice when someone takes the time to invest in a respray of original shade of Y-code Silver Blue metallic.  It has the kind of shine that can be a standout in a crowd.  But more than just paint, it's a true '65 Mustang â€“ the kind of American icon that evokes memories the moment anyone catches sight of the pony on the grille.  So it's hard to go wrong with this classic coupe.  Every piece of brightwork is complete and near pristine, from the wide front bumper, to the side scoops, to the Mustang-branded gas cap.  And everyone love the sight of Mag wheels with pony center caps.  But what really strikes you about this coupe is the straightness of the panels.  We have a large photo file that shows this coupe's journey back from the dead as it undergoes a full rotisserie restoration.

You can tell there was plenty left in the restoration budget to get the interior right. It starts with the factory-correct blue crinkle vinyl seats.  They coordinate nicely with the side panels and even the exterior paint to give this coupe the appeal of a deep blue ocean.  You get all the great iconic features like the bucket seats, dual cowl dash, and the three-spoke sports steering wheel with pony logo center cap.  But then there are also nice subtle upgrades like the retrosound radio that keeps the classic knob-style appearance while upgrading you to a digital AM/FM tuner with cassette player.  Plus, the cold air conditioning has been upgraded to R134a to keep you cool while looking cool.

Under the hood, Ford's trusty and powerful 289 cubic-inch motor is nicely presented.  The bold blue block, valve covers, and air topper all nicely radiating from within the dark engine bay.  You can tell there was a solid investment here, because it has all the right features â€“ from the factory decals to the FoMoCo coolant overflow bag.  It's the kind of total package that will make you proud to show off.  And more than just look good, this is a cool cruiser with features like   the C4 three-speed automatic transmission and modern grip of BF Goodrich T/A tires.

Not only will you love showing off this coupe, but that full restoration photo file will make for a terrific book to take everyone through this icon's rebirth.  It's amazing you can get such a cool car and a cool story for such an exceptional price.  But that's only true if you're first to grab this deal.  Don't miss out, call today!

description: This is a true dream car.  A first-year 1965 Ford Mustang convertible that's such a red-blooded American that it's fully red inside and out.  And because we know you want to drive it, the four-on-the-floor keeps you in complete control of the V8.  Who knew your dream could be this obtainable?

The red is a factory-correct color, and this great pony shows well in the sun.  Iconic cruisers like this always get the attention, and that's why a bright red Mustang is always in demand.  Plus, the sheetmetal must be clean and straight like it is here, because we all look for the iconic full-length scalloped design.  But more than just a nice shine, this one has added attraction from the details like the correct badging, cool chrome bumpers, and the stylish wire wheel covers.

While the white vinyl top has the crisp appearance of a recent investment, we like it even better when the roof is down â€“ that's probably why this was order with a power top! The reason why this looks so good open to the world is because the red seats, red carpets, red door panels, and red dash all coordinate so nicely with the exterior.  There's even a red boot cover.  And everyone loves the look of the premium Pony package interior.  But as much as this classic can carry family and friends, it's really the driver who's the most important.  That's why you get that classic three-spoke sports steering wheel with the perfect thin grip.  And your right hand may never want to leave that Hurst shifter.

Under the hood are some nice upgrades like the Cobra valve covers and the bright air grabber, but there is nothing that gets in the way of the reliable power that comes from Ford's trusty 289 cubic-inch V8.  In fact, this is a true droptop for people who enjoy the feeling of the road.  So you're going to love the total control you get from the four-speed manual transmission, and your favorite soundtrack will be the growl of the dual exhaust as you shift through the optimal powerband.
A red '65 Mustang convertible is the kind of icon that gets all the right attention.  So when it looks great and is priced so right, we know you need to hurry to grab this deal.  Call today!!!

description: The car market is changing rapidly, and perhaps the most surprising thing is that formerly common, affordable cars are now hot collectors' items. VW convertibles, MGBs, and Mustangs like this 1965 coupe are all former bargain-basement dwellers that are no longer second-class citizens. Someone has obviously invested big money in this sleek silver hardtop and it includes all the features you'd want from your favorite pony car.

It's hard to make silver look this good without a lot of time and a lot of money, and that's obviously what happened here. Taking one straight, original car, it was refinished using a lot of hand labor to block the sheetmetal until it was straight enough to calibrate NASA's instruments, then shot with a few coats of the best two-stage urethane you can buy. The gaps are so even and tight that they virtually disappear against the silver body, and it is almost devoid of ornamentation so it looks quite sinister. No modifications mean that it has a classic look, and with GT fog lamps up front and a GT rear valence with exhaust trumpets in back, it's a bit aggressive, too. It's a C-code car, so it came from the factory with a 289, so it's still proudly wearing those emblems on the front fenders. Nice chrome bumpers sparkle against the silvery finish, along with the stainless window surrounds that were polished to a high shine. If you want attention, driving this car will do it.

You'll find black buckets inside, which were standard equipment on all Mustangs. The Pony seat covers, carpets, and headliner are new and an aftermarket center console was added along the way. It's nice to see that they aimed for an OEM look instead of heavy upgrades, and it works just fine in this coupe. Aftermarket A/C was added under the dash and it blows ice cold thanks to modern hardware working behind the scenes. A woodgrained Cobra steering wheel on a tilt steering column frames a set of custom Auto Meter dials in a gauge panel that closely replicates the original GT instruments. Nice! An AM/FM/iPod radio looks quite correct up high in the dash and the trunk is detailed with a recent reproduction mat.

No early Mustang is complete without a 289 under the hood, and the snarky small block that powers this pony has a few upgrades that make it a blast on the street. Inside there's an .040 overbore to add a few cubes, along with ARP head bolts, roller rockers, and a custom cam. Up top, there are Edelbrock aluminum heads, a Holley 4-barrel carburetor, and an upgraded ignition system, all buried under a Cobra air cleaner. The engine is painted correct early-1965 black and starts with a great small block bark from the twin mufflers; there's nothing else that sounds like it. A C4 3-speed automatic transmission with a new torque converter is hardly a demerit thanks to quick reflexes and relaxed cruising capabilities and you're certainly not going to hurt the 8-inch rear end by having a little fun on the street.
